<div id="review_41825909" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/41825909" />
    <a title="Jonathan N" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/706901-jonathan-n"><img alt="Jonathan N" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/41825909?book_show_action=true">Jan 04, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jonathan N" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jonathan N" href="/user/show/706901-jonathan-n">Jonathan N</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer41825909" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11483446671132108480">The first half of this book is the best thing I&apos;ve read in years. The stories of Dylan Ebdus growing up in Brooklyn, dealing with racism and graffiti and superpowers, were amazing. I couldn&apos;t put the book down. I loved it.<br/><br/>But then the timeline jumps forward into the 90s. Instead of a shy middle-school student, or a punk poseur teenager, Dylan is a whiny rock journalist in 1999. That&apos;s not the book I want to read. I don&apos;t care about his problems with his girlfriend or efforts to pitch a movie dea</span>
  <span id="freeText11483446671132108480" style="display:none">The first half of this book is the best thing I've read in years. The stories of Dylan Ebdus growing up in Brooklyn, dealing with racism and graffiti and superpowers, were amazing. I couldn't put the book down. I loved it.<br /><br />But then the timeline jumps forward into the 90s. Instead of a shy middle-school student, or a punk poseur teenager, Dylan is a whiny rock journalist in 1999. That's not the book I want to read. I don't care about his problems with his girlfriend or efforts to pitch a movie deal. The sudden change in focus, and the switch from 3rd to 1st person, made me feel like I was reading a different book. A much worse book.<br /><br />Once I got over my disappointment at the change in the second half, and my desire to stop reading entirely, I found it wasn't all bad. There were some flashbacks to Dylan's time in college, which I enjoyed. And the ending was interesting. I'm still giving the book 4 stars because I loved the first half so much, but I'm disappointed by it overall.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11483446671132108480" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


