<div id="review_904348001" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/904348001" />
    <a title="Andrew" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/442654-andrew"><img alt="Andrew" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1513093267p2/442654.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/904348001?book_show_action=true">Apr 07, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Andrew" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Andrew" href="/user/show/442654-andrew">Andrew</a>
      </span>

          added it




        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/442654-andrew?shelf=american-fiction">american-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/442654-andrew?shelf=2000s-american-fiction">2000s-american-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer904348001" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15301192228926228670">Jonathan Lethem has a unique talent for fantastic narrative structure-- just really great structural chops-- paired with dreadful, dreadful phrasing. Just horrible, embarrassing, aching-to-be-hip kind of descriptions (on the shit list there with Richard Russo and Michael Cunningham).<br/><br/>But the thing is, the sum works. It&apos;s a good story, a fully realized novel. Flawed, yes, cloying, sometimes, but a very worthy summer read, and often damn fun.</span>
  <span id="freeText15301192228926228670" style="display:none">Jonathan Lethem has a unique talent for fantastic narrative structure-- just really great structural chops-- paired with dreadful, dreadful phrasing. Just horrible, embarrassing, aching-to-be-hip kind of descriptions (on the shit list there with Richard Russo and Michael Cunningham).<br /><br />But the thing is, the sum works. It's a good story, a fully realized novel. Flawed, yes, cloying, sometimes, but a very worthy summer read, and often damn fun.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15301192228926228670" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


